Traveling through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical help to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in the West African country, just one for 5,000 people
Match here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to vote for him to the "CNN Hero of the Year."
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father keep losing consciousness and traveling to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation formed, which spread to his brain and caused a hematoma there, which was to affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," comments Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet you are not first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has barely changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
There is only one doctor in Cameroon for 5,000 people each, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” Bwelle said.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffering in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it matured.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team have conducted 700 free surgeries in the last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and provides free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and drive with the tied-up medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Everything does not always go smoothly.
More than once, they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will receive like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a cause for celebration and Bwelle – with his broad smile and limitless energy – likes to be present at the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates – a document required for school but simply unable to afford many poor families.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, the town hall or an apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go into the recreation area to make way for the next.
The lighting for the surgery and disinfection equipment is fed by the group's generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday.
It's a busy workload, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” Bwelle says.
On Sunday, the team then heads back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has conducted 700 free surgeries in the last year and knows that with its work it makes a huge difference for the people it helps.
A man explained that the free operation of a hernia he had received was now allowing him to return to work.
“This is changing the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his charitable work, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's asleep," says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia for her second year and volunteers to join Bwelle's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain hands-on experience they would never get at home.
“We can be involved in operations where we can help tap blood or the instruments for Dr. Bwelle hold," O'Malley explains.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
The students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and frequently bring donated medical supplies.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and guidance.
"He's a hero without a doubt," says O'Malley.
He devotes his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives and thus fulfill a promise he has made to his father gives him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this work," Bwelle said.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
