Pope Francis appoints first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will be on 22. February for the first time new cardinals of the Catholic Church appointed, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the most senior clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who elect a pope, so that Francis will thus appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached an age of 80 can no longer participate in the papal election – this is the case with a group of 120 “eligible cardinals”.
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a spokesman for the Vatican, said it would hold a meeting of all the cardinals before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as the Consistory, was held.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the consistory in advance in February so that other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from around the world can be planned,” Lombardi said.
Catholic Voices' Jack Valero said the number of eligible cardinals was likely to have dropped by February.
He declared that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as necessary so that the number of cardinals entitled to vote would again be 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he would like.
The consistory next year is significant because it is the first since the election of Francis in March this year, according to Valero.
There is currently a certain overhang on the part of Europe and in particular of Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint Cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from around the world who have the mandate to find opportunities to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything alone.
"Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him," Valero said.
He declared that it was "well possible" that Francis asks the Cardinals for advice.
But so far we have not been in this situation – this is all completely new.
Valero said that typically the bishops from large places would be called to cardinals, but Francis is “full of surprises – so we do not know who he is appointing.”
