Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing the economy to the same table and defining what those who are responsible for prosperity and work in the UK would like to change in our relations with the EU.
To that end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders and asked them what they think about the UK, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed over 1,000 business executives, roughly reflecting UK business sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies now export outside Europe and focus on countries that modernize and grow while states in the EU are stagnant.
They want the government to favour new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil, instead of dwelling on the long and exhausting process of reforming the obscure EU institutions.
When asked about their view on certain legally regulated issues – from antitrust to product legislation – the majority of business leaders believe that control over these key competences should be brought back to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction about the single market, as, according to the company, the cost of the Brussels rules would now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe’s trade zone – even 40 percent of large companies agreed, which are traditionally the most pro-European.
Finally, and this presumably says most, our survey of business leaders revealed that a clear majority want a course from Britain towards changing the deal and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This finding, which is found among companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that the economy is pushing for a "meaningful change" that brings the booklet of action back to the UK.
It's about a lot - a change to the deal and better conditions for Britain would lead to a change of opinion in favour of remaining in the EU in a referendum at 16 per cent.
The prime minister should have no doubts: this poll shows that the UK economy stands behind his plan for the renegotiations of UK terms for EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a significant shift in power relations back to the UK from a renegotiation.
A better deal for the UK economy is possible and increasingly necessary after the eurozone is now moving towards a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the result of our survey shows, which means increased attention for businesses to trade and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to regulations.
