Scientists were able to shed more light on the connection between a dog's tail-wagging and mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wagged their tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while it was the left side in nervous dogs.
Yet now scientists are saying that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain react differently to stimuli that produce positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right hemisphere of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail wagging of their conspecifics, the researchers monitored the animals while these films looked at other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the cock moves in one direction, sometimes in the other
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs films with dogs - either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog move the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was primarily to the left (again from the perspective of the dog that wags), so their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs and the wagging is linked to the tail in one direction rather with friendly behavior and the right side rather produces a less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, vets and trainers to better understand their animal's emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behavior and visiting fellow at the Faculty of Veterinology at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it is a contented dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, the following was: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when his ‘tail’ is wagging on the left and not right instead of becoming restless – just the other way around than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
“Although there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior can be easily recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
