In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so great that ValueMax, where it made its exchange, became the third pawn shop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pledging jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 Singapore in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore require an effective annual rate of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent that United Overseas Bank is demanding, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping centre.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that no creditworthiness or proof of income is required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
This is why millions of people in the region turn to pawnshops after families feel the pressure from rising living costs, as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose fiscal policy in the developed economic areas, families with lower and middle incomes seek out pawn shops to make up for the difference in the event of a stuttering economy.
This week, rating agency Standard & Poor's grew household debt, mostly due to rising mortgages, described as a risk factor for the credit rating of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product, according to the agency.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, a 60 percent increase still in 2008.
Economists are also worried about Thailand's high consumer debt, which narrowly emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed continued existing export weakness and a slackening in consumer demand.
“In the end, in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have further heightened the trend towards pledging personal belongings, as people take the opportunity to turn the family's jewellery into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city-state's 200 pawn stores are gold.
People say to themselves, “The price of gold looks good, let’s pledge grandmother’s gold chain and bring it back next month.”
Thailand's largest pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in customers in its stores in recent months.
The growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is funding that with 60 percent of the $66 million it took in this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawn shops not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase debt.
"Customers borrow items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables does not increase household schooling," she explains.
The pawnshop business is increasingly accepted as short-term, hedged financing.
Also, not all people who use pawnshops are in financial trouble.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax's stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
“This includes wealthy people who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses that need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow,” says Yeah.
