Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, as research shows.
Physical changes do not yet directly mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe the epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced among boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics Association this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time calming parents down - usually this is not an indication that puberty is now fast," explained Kaplowitz.
Obvious indications of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair as well as body odor, are evident in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (occurrence of the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When the development of the breasts begins, it will take at least two to three years to menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with this Common Problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually represents the beginning of puberty, but it is "early" if breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight years.
In most cases, the process slows or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests by an endicronologist could be indicated so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and defending against another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the speed of development, the growth rate and the emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication, but he admits: “The suppression of puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and the feelings of girls, unlike being their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don't want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter got her days at ten.
Even though there were initial signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home frightened and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many comprehensively published theories about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no conclusive evidence that hormones are causative in milk or other food, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media.
Boys, like girls, come to puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a study in 2001 on girls aged six to nine years, which establishes a link between body fat and entering puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that have played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to the climate to the genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and pubic hair is growing earlier, the trend towards full-scale earlier puberty is not as pronounced as it is in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underscored the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even among babies and young children.
"We need to be careful about how to identify the true beginning of puberty," Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This can mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz advised.
When you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who blossom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it enters earlier than thought.
