What happens to my email on the way?
Email is actually an electronic letter.
Was the draft of the Internet service e-mail technically implemented the letter secret similar to the conventional post office?
When designing the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols did not make sure to create a stable foundation for a hearing-proof exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional email corresponds to an open postcard rather than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna’s e-mail program or browser sends the email to the mail server of your service provider.
For example, if she has a GMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run on several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content at his provider.
Are conventional emails read along the way through the net?
Most mails are read several times on the go by software robots.
The provider of the sender is usually checked whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is a nuisance and unwanted spam mail, which is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the emails?
The probability of unauthorized persons reading an email is extremely low.
In theory, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the option of reading electronic mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal options to intercept or take note of emails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect emails against reading?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to obscure the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even possible to easily identify who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the email market in Germany?
In the mainly privately used mailboxes, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role, according to a study by Convios Consulting from August 2013.
While Yahoo-Mail's shares had fallen recently, GMail was able to grow significantly from Google.
