Royal Commission hearing: Two YMCA staff charged over allegations of sexual offences against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) had been charged with sexual offences related to children before allegations were made against child caretaker Jonathan Lord from Caringbah in 2011, the Royal Commission for Child Sexual Abuse Learned.
However, in the opening statement before the Commission, the YMCA had said that “it had never had to deal with an incident of child sexual abuse in the organization.”
Managing director Phillip Hare was questioned about a case in which a YMCA employee had been charged with child pornography offences, and another in which a sports teacher at YMCA Caringbah Hall had been convicted of abusing children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare said Gail Furness, a commission's assistant lawyer, said he had known about the first case but did not know the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA's opening statement to the Commission was also inaccurate in the claim that "there have been external reviews of the YMCA, in which the YMCA was recognised as at the forefront of child safety."
Evidence before the Commission rather shows that the YMCA has been informed that it has received the second lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit of the Department of Education and Communities in August of the year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA at 21, acknowledged that the management had failed "from me down" in hiring Lord and failed to ensure that employees had been aware of their obligations to report violations of child safety guidelines.
Lord had been convicted earlier this year of sex offences against twelve boys during his two years of work for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare denied, however, that the YMCA had a cultural issue that had prevented employees from reporting Lord's violations regarding child safety.
Staff testified that they had observed violations, among other things, that Lord was alone with children, privately looked after them as a babysitter, let them sit on his lap, said to one that he loved it, and let children play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose superior was Lord and who had asked for child protection training because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that the child service manager Jacqui Barnat, who was the superior of Lords at the YMCA Caringbah, was "very intimidating and very unapproachable most of the time."
The managing director explained that he would not accept statements from employees that they had not dared to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, rather, their friendship with Lord had impaired their judgment, which is why they had not reported him.
Hare said he had told the board of the YMCA NSW his view that the lesson the organization had to draw from the "Jonathan Lord incident" was "not about reporting" by employees, and the board had agreed to it.
Hare said the decision to push employees to sign nonsecration commitments shortly after the allegations were made by the executive director of the YMCA's children's services, Liam Whitley.
He said that this should prevent contamination of the evidence, but this was "overzealous" and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW had not been an organization safe for children during the period when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert in child sexual abuse, explained to the commission.
He explained that there had been "serious problems" in hiring, reviewing, training and supervising employees.
The hearing was up to 20. December adjourned.
Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At a length of around 120 metres, a sewer from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
If you visit Cologne, you will not be able to avoid the cathedral.
Around 157 metres, the two towers rise into the sky and make it the second highest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors who marvel at the two filigree church towers suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the field of Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for its guided tours is the Cologne-Tourismus Service Center directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a city suitable for the car, and therefore of the remains of the old city wall, only what was not too big remained.
Most users of the parking garage therefore rush past the Roman remains today and only park their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal grids in the parking deck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins of palm-sized stones.
"It's remnants of the Roman city wall that was built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze recounts.
Before it goes back to light, Schulze lets the participants take a look at the upper parking level in a dark, 15-meter-deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the praetorium, and here the participants descend into the depths again.
We are witnessing here the official seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the preator of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which means in good German as much as "City of Roman law and city of the Agrippinensians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the Praetorium is the former governor's palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the anteroom of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here over a length of around 120 metres.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima, if you want," Schulze cheers up the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After pulling the key at the cash register, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the mikvah, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater that was essential for the ritual ablutions.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikveh, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The mikvah will become part of an archaeological zone on City Hall Square, for which construction work is scheduled to begin shortly.
However, a few more years will pass before completion.
