George Kerevan: European unbundling gives the Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story for independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
That provides the keyword for stories about passport checks in Berwick and a border secured with barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
In fact, the Strathclyde template pointed out the possible economic benefits that more freedom of travel would bring in the rest of Europe, but this did not matter – as expected – in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favourable to them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued non-observance for Brussels would only be a small concession in return for what you really want from the Scots.
Not really a story.
And one that has come in such a year that it already resembles a fossil: For the first time I heard the "independence means passport control" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should you expect an independent Scotland to dance to the European whistle?
Why trade the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unify Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project has officially died.
All over the EU, parties are gaining ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic party Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – was able to win almost five million votes in the federal election in September and thus effectively drive the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the straitjacket, into which the respective national economy is forced by sticking to the common currency, many people are of the view that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – that was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave it that way.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage against Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending – spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the "green" energy directives prescribed by Brussels - a code for the subsidisation of French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays double for electricity and four times for gas compared to the United States.
That's a crippling cost disadvantage, as we've already seen in Grangemouth.
All of the world's wage fixings do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is coming up, especially in France, the EU's former cheerleader.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle with which Germany could be kept in check and Paris lifted on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, which is the struggling French economy.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive by-election, thus relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the electoral vote - a timely warning to Britain's Labour party that it can't assume a split on the right-wing spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newfound popularity among working-class white French?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-common currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties perform well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to go beyond: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favoured.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold on to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flottering itself with the US.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can choose to be a region of (in the final analysis) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including to say to Berlin and Brussels what they can put somewhere.
I suspect Scotland could drive quite well in a looser European network, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and retain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour finance minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to then be forced on an austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but don't make cell phone calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices for reading, working, playing, music and using watching movies from departure to landing, but not on the phone, according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the U.S. on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depended on the respective airline, explained FAA employee Michael Huerta at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the air staff training manuals and the arrangements for storing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines seeking to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among those airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers will have to shut down smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not take them off again until the aircraft has reached an altitude of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
Upon entry into the landing approach, passengers must switch them off again and are not allowed to take off again before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA explained.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been converted for the use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit,” Glading commented.
We are honestly tired of having to feel like watchers on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections for surfing, exchanging e-mails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are being asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still not a "Words With Friends," the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to publicly leave a jet from American Airlines because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight also remain prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone conversations lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices on take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, safety expert on national traffic issues on CBS News, said cellphones would still be considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also disrupt transmission towers,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee launched by the FAA to investigate this issue last month recommended that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA to loosen restrictions on use has increased.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies mention that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the shutdown of the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966 after reports of interference with navigation and communication equipment by passenger-carryed FM radios became known, which represented the latest technical trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA in such a way that they do not mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers for several years when the altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when flipping around.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transfer values are stronger.
Amazon.com is one of the advocates for a relaxation of restrictions on device use by passengers.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but were unable to detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk involved in using equipment.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Association of Airline Passengers, said he felt the disruption by the devices was genuine, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports from pilots who speak for a disruption of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the disconnection of the devices by the passengers when landing instruments in poor visibility.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adjustment for travellers who would be extensively equipped with technology today.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of U.S. Travel Association.
