Jumbo manufacturers argue in face of large orders over seat width
There has been an altercation between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of seats in the tourist class on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a bitter clash at the Dubai Airshow this month.
The dispute revolves around the width of the seat that is offered to passengers on long flights in the tourist class – not always those airlines are most concerned about, but this designated space is the key to the efficiency claims on the latest Airbus SAS and Boeing Co. aircraft.
Airbus this week called for an industry standard that prescribes a seat width of at least 46 cm (18 inches) in the tourist class, yet U.S. arch-rival Boeing says airlines should decide that.
The dispute comes at a time when the aircraft manufacturers are vying to sell even larger versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft, and at the event from 17 to 21. November expect record orders.
How the rear part of the aircraft is designed – especially whether there are rows with nine or ten seats – is crucial for the stated economic results that the new "mini-jumbo" design is to deliver.
Boeing claims its modernized "777X" holds 406 people at seats in the tourist class, which are over 17 inches wide and thus allow ten per row.
Airbus says the competing version of the A350 carries 350 people in 18-inch-wide seats in the tourist class, with nine per row.
Aircraft giants often hand out blows about technical details by means of advertising in the trade press.
Now Airbus is appealing directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to make the race with over 100 orders.
Recently, the company unveiled an ad that could be the start of a new ad war and showed donors a picture in which three people sit squeezed in a restaurant, and the title: "Would you accept that?"
"Boeing proposes long-haul flights in seats that are tighter than regional turbo props," says Airbus sales chief John Leahy.
In the face of changing dietary habits, people are getting fatter, but aircraft seats have not changed radically.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 defined modern long-haul travel, and the end of the century, the weight of the male average American between the ages of 40 and 49 increased by 10 percent, according to data from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
The waist circumference of the male average American in the 21. Century is 100.8 cm, according to U.S. health statistics.
Airbus says its rival adheres to a seating concept from the 1950s, when the average body circumference of the freshly christened "Jet Set" was narrower.
According to Airbus, investigations have been carried out that show that an additional tariff (2.54 cm) per seat increased the sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing denies Airbus' figures on seat dimensions and says it is not at the discretion of manufacturers to decide how airlines are shaping the balance between air fares and facility.
The company also explains that, according to research, the experience in the aircraft depends on more than the width of the seat.
“It really boils down to giving airlines flexibility so they can do what they think they need to succeed,” said Kent Craver, a flight cabin expert at Boeing.
They don't want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable.
They know their business better than anyone.
For passengers, it is about more elbow-free, but for manufacturers it is increasingly becoming an issue that can affect sales.
Behind the dispute is a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least $700 billion by list prices in the coming decades, which could have a lasting impact on the export balance of the US or Europe.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seat layout is the driving force behind the dispute over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest twin-engine long-haul designs than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing's statements on the results depend in part on the 777 compare the 777X with its ten seats per row with the original design of nine seats in the 777.
The increased cost per unit is still lower than with currently used machines with ten seats per row.
"Boeing is therefore squeezing more seats into his aircraft to make it more competitive with our products," says Kevin Keniston, Head of Passenger Comfort at Europe's Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say full cabins with ten seats per row at existing 777s suggested that many passengers opted for the tighter arrangement, which could be accompanied by cheaper air fares.
“Eighteen-inch seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is: from an economic point of view, the Airbus offer is controlled by the threat of the 777,” says Mary Kirby, expert in cabin furnishings, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which the airlines can choose.
The world-traveling jet sellers even carry tape measure with them to measure the facility in the competition.
Even if they praise the comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with a highly compacted design for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seat rows, but has not yet sold one, according to its own statement.
Until recently, Airbus has stressed the importance of more customizability of cabins and offering wide seats at the aisles for some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of major modern jets, experts say the call for a new industry standard is likely to fizzle out, but could distract from the wave of 777X sales.
