New anti-nicotine vaccine could put a stop to the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Before human testing, more attempts are needed, which may take a few more years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results were good.
“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and have tried all the methods available on the market, but have had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” said Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been altered to include the genetic information on the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, so that a smoker does not experience nicotine high.
In trials, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal activity level.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, had taken a "time-out," the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain the antibody level that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is probably significantly lower, because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is quite sure, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that smokers would use it to stop.
"They know that when they start smoking again, they don't feel any pleasure because of the nicotini vaccine, and that helps them to put off the habit," he explains.
