Frontier Airlines charges fees for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 from passengers who want to stow on their carry-on luggage.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for a piece of carry-on luggage and $2 for coffee or lemonade, even if it was read in Wednesday's announcement that passengers are likely to keep the whole can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small bags under the seat are still free of charge.
Frontier said it charges $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 for travelers who only paid at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee was aimed at getting travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
"We don't want to calculate that sum," she explained.
Airlines began charging fees for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid them have therefore stuffed as much as possible into hand luggage, which means that the luggage compartments above the seat are often overcrowded.
Fees are a way to persuade passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee isn't really about making money.
It is about the most loyal customers of Frontier, who have clearly expressed that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy your tickets on the airline's website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger may be allowed to take a piece of luggage with him free of charge at the frontier gate, but the next person may have to pay $100 for a comparable piece of luggage.
O'Malley said Frontier's website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers were notified of the fee before they came to the gate.
Frontier's new hand luggage fee won't come into effect until the summer, an exact date does not yet exist.
Passengers often scold baggage surcharges and other fees, but airlines like to resort to it.
They argue that transporting the luggage costs money and passengers should pay for that service if they wished it.
Many on Wall Street view the new baggage fees as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most have so far left the fingers of charges for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for carry-on baggage three years ago and later followed Allegiant Air, also a low-cost airline.
The only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who is closely following the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the hand luggage fee Spirit brings in $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who formerly held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what would await him at the gate if passengers were faced with the company's unusual carry-on baggage fee.
“The boarding process was among the smoothest I have experienced in my career in aviation,” he said.
I expected to see teeth grinding and tangible discussions on the gate.
