Frontier also follows Spirit at the $2 charged for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company said passengers who bought lemonade or juice were allowed to keep the whole can and coffee would be refilled for free.
Water is still free.
US Airways briefly tried to charge money for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed it seven months later after passengers complained and no other large company had followed suit.
Frontier's move to charge fees for carry-on baggage if passengers don't buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to direct customers to their own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies such as Orbitz $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This provides an incentive for all companies to persuade passengers to buy directly from them instead of via an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, the company began to award only half as many frequent flyer miles when booking through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were cut once again to 25 percent of the flight route.
A flight booked with a third-party provider with Frontier over 1000 miles therefore only earns customers 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats only when buying directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its headquarters in Denver, but the business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
