The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the kilometres driven – and possibly also where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax assessments.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The U.S. Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and voices a number of privacy concerns.
But while you can’t agree on a course of action in Congress, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how to switch to a system over the course of the next ten years where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of motorists have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS surveillance.
This is truly a must for our country.
"It's not something we're just going to possibly use," said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, which is planning a record of miles driven among all California motorists in the state from 2025.
The way we pay those taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from taxes that pay Americans at the fuel dispenser, is broke.
