His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to be used to test a mile-based payment system.
"This is the most sensible alternative in the long term," he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is well received by urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence the driving behavior in such a way that traffic jams and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
California planners are relying on the system for developing strategies designed to achieve the state's ambitious, legally enshrined climate change targets.
But Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The Reason Foundation’s free marketers are also impressed by the idea of letting drivers pay after the distance has travelled.
“This isn’t a tax that disappears into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of guidelines at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two previous American transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, had called on Congress to move towards mile-based billing.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
Yet the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the push, responding to concerns from lawmakers from rural areas representing people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Several states and major cities are nevertheless moving in this direction on their own.
The most dedicated is Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the petroleum tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering one.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how one might introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, motorists were skeptical at the thought the government could track any of its movements.
"Concerns about Big Brother and things like this have been a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at Nevada's Transportation Department.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into mature surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is among a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that the state can use to capture the kilometers driven, but not exactly when and where.
With that, according to Khan, the public would be more reassured, too.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The firm did not originally compete to help states tax motorists.
