However, some traffic planners wonder whether all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or annual levy could be imposed on motorists with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is sufficient," said Randy Rentschler, the Commission's head of legislation and public affairs.
