Desperation of an Obama voter
I voted President Obama twice in the hope that change is possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that had been thwarted by Republicans' blockade tactics
The blockade policy does not excuse Obamacare's website problems, the drone strikes
Obama's memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what would have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a terribly sad book.
It's a book I thought would cheer me up during the murky second year of my medical studies and give me hope again.
It is called "The Audacity to Win" and describes the memoirs of Barack Obama on the 2008 presidential election.
When I’m done with my patient records in the evening and going to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take their breath away from a speech.
The election became a landslide victory and news anchors paused to show the historical significance of that hour.
My classmates cried with joy and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama moved into office in 2008, he had 82% approval ratings.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a rude awakening, as if you are being ripped out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem like a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I acknowledge the great and multifaceted things Obama has achieved, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for Health Insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced silence of homosexuality in the Army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, am of the view that the partisan blockade tactics have overturned too many aspirations to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and closing down Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to an end with my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why one allows the eavesdropping of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers are being punished who expose state misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are circumvented during the presidential election.
It does not justify the findings of a report that said the White House’s efforts to immobilize the media are the “most aggressive since the Nixon administration.”
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that government work could contradict the political campaigns that it was going beyond.
Obviously, the deputies' office is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events like the Newtown massacre shape public discussion.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and unsophisticated alternative, he did not seem to be able to set his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of for so long.
But with the decline in approval ratings for Obama to below 45% this week, the return to 2008 through this book has become all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have dissolved into air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama had to take a heavy loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania primaries.
In a meeting with the election workers after the decision, he told his staff they had to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
“I want us to find our magic again,” he said.
We have to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree with you any stronger.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
